<HEAD>SECTION XVII. MADNESS&mdash;INSANIA.</HEAD>
<P>THIS is divided into two &s;pecies&mdash;MANIA, <HI>furious madne&s;s</HI> and MELANCHOLIA, <HI>glooomy madne&s;s.</HI> Notwith&s;tanding which divi&s;ion, authors have con&s;idered them only as different degrees of the &s;ame di&s;ea&s;e; which is defined an alienation, of the mind, or deviation from the rules of &s;ound rea&s;on&mdash;or a con&s;tant delirium without fever.</P>
<P>This doctrine has been long given us by ARETAEUS <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> TRALLIAN. The <HI>former</HI> a&s;&s;erts, that melancholy is the begin|ning and origin of mania, into which it glides more from incre<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> that any other cau&s;e&mdash;the <HI>latter,</HI> that mania is nothing more than melancholy brought to a greater degree; as, on account of their clo&s;e connection, the tran&s;ition becomes extremely <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> from one di&s;ea&s;e to the other. And HOFFMAN, imbibing the opinion, advances, that from attentive practice and ob&s;ervation we learn, that both di&s;ea&s;es ari&s;e from the &s;ame origin and con|taining cau&s;e, and vary only in degree and time of inva&s;ion, that melancholy may be ju&s;tly received as the primary di&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters"> but mania as its exacerbation and accidental effect&mdash;which con|nection daily and every clo&s;e ob&s;ervation confirms; for melan|cholic people, particularly if the di&s;ea&s;e has been of long &s;tand|ing very readily fall into mania; which ea&s;ing, melancholy <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> turns again; although afterwards, at certain periods, they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> again be revi&s;ited by mania.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION, The MELANCHOLIC are thus affected they appear &s;ad, dejected, dull, without any real cau&s;e&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> are &s;eized with fear and trembling&mdash;encouraged with diffic<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">&mdash;are watchful&mdash;love &s;olitude&mdash;prone to anger, and mutab<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> enquiring after the mo&s;t minute trifles, covetous, but &s;oon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;imple and profu&s;e&mdash;their habits are co&s;tive; &s;ometimes has <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> no &s;tools at all; &s;ometimes they are round and dry, &s;urrounded with a black bilious fluid&mdash;they make &s;mall quantities of uri<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> and that acrid and bilious&mdash;have great flatulence at the pi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the &s;tomach&mdash;putrid eructations, foetid and offen&s;ive; and &s;ome times a &s;harp liquid with bile is rejected&mdash;the face is pallid&mdash;the pul&s;e is &s;mall, dull, and weak&mdash;and the &s;ick are at <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> extremely voracious.</P>
<P>The MANIACAL, rou&s;ed to anger, are wild with rage&mdash;&s;ome run a great way&mdash;&s;ome bawl out violently&mdash;&s;ome fly from the
<PB N="433" REF="028021_0429_0FD673AA435E2308">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ght of men into &s;olitude, and only conver&s;e by them&s;elves&mdash;&s;ome cut and tear their limbs.&mdash;In the height of the di&s;ea&s;e, during &s;leep they are di&s;turbed with vi&s;ion, are immoderately la&s;civious, and openly, without fear or &s;hame, gratify their de&s;ires&mdash;but when the di&s;ea&s;e abates, they are quiet, &s;tupid, and &s;orrowful&mdash;al&s;o, coming to the knowledge of their malady, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> are oppre&s;&s;ed with grief at their own calamity and mi&s;ery.</P>
<P>The&s;e are the &s;ymptoms which denote the pre&s;ence, or decli|ning &s;tate of mania. The following are &s;uch as appear <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> the attack, at lea&s;t a few of them which have been <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ob&s;erved.</P>
<P>The eyes are red and &s;uffu&s;ed with blood&mdash;there is an <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> vibration of the eye-lids&mdash;their u&s;ual mode of conduct is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;pride manife&s;ting it&s;elf in their countenance, voice, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;they grind their teeth&mdash;conceive a hatred for this or particular per&s;on&mdash;get little &s;leep&mdash;have violent head-ach, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> quickne&s;s of hearing&mdash;ringing of the ears, and mu&s;ical <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">. To this place is worthy to be referred the remarkable <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of limbs, and incredible capability of bearing cold, of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> maniacal &s;ubjects, in the increa&s;e of di&s;ea&s;e, are po&s;&s;e&s;&s;|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in women, the collection of blood in the brea&s;ts. <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> people afflicted with madne&s;s are not &s;ubject to be affected <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> epidemic di&s;ea&s;e; and are often cured of other <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> under which they labour, or have their progre&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> during their &s;tate of in&s;anity.</P>
<P>The greate&s;t part of this de&s;cription, exact and elegant as it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> been handed down from ARETAEOS, and copied by mo&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> moderns: and in examining the whole of the &s;ymptoms, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;trike us pretty clearly that they mu&s;t flow from &s;ome <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of tho&s;e parts which are con&s;idered as the &s;eat of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, &s;en&s;ation, and voluntary motion; and the&s;e are the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> portions of the brain. Even from HIPPOCRATES the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> have been &s;aid to be borrowed, "for," &s;ays he, &s;peak|ing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the brain, <Q>from this part derive we wi&s;dom, and under|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="8 letters">, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ear, &s;ee, and know good from bad; and al&s;o from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> we in&s;ane.</Q></P>
<P>CAUSES. Tho&s;e which are con&s;idered the <HI>remote</HI> or <HI>inducing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ental</HI> or <HI>corporeal</HI>&mdash;the mind being too &s;trongly, or too <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> continued fixed upon one object&mdash;grief, fear, hope, joy, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> love, totally ab&s;orbing the faculties of the mind&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> dread of Divine vengeance, from the fal&s;e principles <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> religion;&mdash;the membranes of the brain indurated&mdash;dryne&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the brain&mdash;of where the di&s;ea&s;e is hereditary&mdash;too &s;edentary life&mdash;poi&s;ons po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed of a &s;tupifying power&mdash;immoderate
