<HEAD>SECTION XVIII. AFFECTIONS OF THE LUNGS.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. COMMON COUHG, OR TUSSIS.</HEAD>
<P>THIS complaint is &s;o common, and &s;o often experienced by al|mo&s;t every individual, that a minute de&s;cription &s;eems un|nece&s;&s;ary; but as from neglect it may be, and is frequently, at|tended with di&s;agreeable con&s;equences, it will be u&s;eful to &s;ee <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the&s;e originate, in order to &s;hew the nece&s;&s;ity of attending to this complaint, though apparently trivial, and taking it off by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> readie&s;t and ea&s;ie&s;t means, in order to prevent &s;ub&s;equent mi&s;|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="5 letters">;&mdash;to this, which is occa&s;ioned by what is called catching <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cold, and the hooping, or convul&s;ive cough, we &s;hall confine our&s;elves.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the fir&s;t we &s;ay, a cough is a concu&s;&s;ion of the lungs <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> at uncertain periods, induced by &s;ome irritating cau&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> on their internal &s;urface, or that of the windpipe, (29.) <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> quick reiterated action of the mu&s;cles of the ribs, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, (33.) and belly; and this irritating cau&s;e by &s;ome <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ob&s;tructs per&s;piration, and determines the matter, which <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> pa&s;s off by the per&s;pirable pores, too freely to that or|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">, or part leading to it&mdash;and chiefly, as it is termed, from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">hing cold, for the mo&s;t part attended with hoar&s;ene&s;s, run|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">g of the no&s;e, &s;neezing, chillne&s;s, and &s;ometimes with &s;light degrees of febrile affections. People thus affected generally cough up mucus from the lungs, now and then of a yellowi&s;h colour, and vi&s;cid; which, when expectorated, puts a period to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> of coughing for that time.</P>
<P>From what has been &s;aid, the indications of cure will be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>To remove the irritating cau&s;e, and guard the lungs, &s;o that, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> it is removed, they &s;hall not feel too &s;en&s;ibly the effects of that &s;timulus&mdash;and the&s;e are performed by re&s;toring per&s;piration&mdash;evacuating the morbid mucus, &s;heathing its acrimony, ren|dering the lungs in&s;en&s;ible to its effects&mdash;and giving proper &s;trength to the ve&s;&s;els of the lungs; for, by the repeated &s;hocks and di&s;ten&s;ion, they become debilitated.</P>
<P>And the&s;e will be accompli&s;hed, for the mo&s;t part, by very ea&s;y means&mdash;by avoiding cold&mdash;keeping the brea&s;t warm, by
<PB N="440" REF="028021_0436_0FD6737F7941FD50">
wearing flannel over it, drinking warm liquids in the morning, and at meals warm water, or inhaling the vapour&mdash;taking the compound decoction of barley, lin&s;eed, or bran-tea, with honey and nitre&mdash;or drinking at night barley-water, &s;weetened and warm, in which is di&s;&s;olved the yolk of an egg, or taking any gentle diaphoretics, (178.) or &s;mall do&s;es of antimonial powder, (180.)&mdash;the&s;e, or &s;ome of the&s;e, early applied, will readily prove effectual.</P>
<P>But &s;hould the complaint be ob&s;tinate and violent, bleeding may be nece&s;&s;ary, and a &s;pare diet&mdash;&s;aline, and antimonial me|dicines may be given, (No. 6 to 9.) to which may be added camphorated tincture of opium, (152.) or nitrous medicines, (No. 2.) may be joined with antimonials, and &s;ome of the li|quids before &s;poken of adhered to&mdash;the body &s;hould al&s;o be kept open, and the urinary di&s;charge promoted, by gentle a|perients and diuretics&mdash;linctu&s;&s;es and emul&s;ions, (No. 81 to 84.) may al&s;o be occa&s;ionally admini&s;tered; and are very u&s;eful, if &s;wallowed gradually, particularly &s;hould there be a tickling up|on the top of the windpipe, which &s;ometimes appears to be the principal cau&s;e of a cough, e&s;pecially in the beginning.</P>
<P>At the latter end of the complaint, if the cough &s;hould con|tinue, though not violent, but come on now and then, and there &s;hould be expectorated tough, vi&s;cid mucus, the ammoniacal mixture, (No. 141, 143.) given three or four times a day, I have found &s;erviceable, not only in promoting an ea&s;y expec|toration, but &s;trengthening the ve&s;&s;els of the lungs&mdash;and where I find people &s;ubject to frequent returns, after the cure, benefit may be derived in the prevention, by bark given twice a day for a little time.</P>
<P>During the &s;everity of the complain<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the patient &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> advi&s;ed to keep much within doors, avoid the night air, be rather warmly clothed&mdash;particularly keep the feet warm&mdash;and by the&s;e means &s;ucce&s;s is certain.</P>
<P>But &s;hould the complaint be long neglected, from the repeat|ed &s;tre&s;&s;es laid upon the lungs by continually coughing, hard glandular tumors, called tubercles, are <HI>not rarely</HI> formed&mdash;&s;ometimes the ve&s;&s;els of the lungs are ruptured, by the blood, being &s;o often too forcibly thrown into them&mdash;in both of which, con&s;umptions have been the con&s;equence&mdash;the cough then be|gins to put on another a&s;pect, and induce a di&s;ea&s;e of a very &s;e|rious nature; for the relief of which the reader is referred to Pulmonary Con&s;umption. (331.)</P>
