<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 2. HOOPING, OR CONVULSIVE COUGH.</HEAD>
<P>It is &s;o called from the violence of the concu&s;&s;ions, and that
<PB N="441" REF="028021_0437_0FD76EAE03762F48">
particular noi&s;e of hooping which is ob&s;ervable in the fits of coughing&mdash;al&s;o CHINCOUGH, from the Dutch word <HI>kincken,</HI> to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">nt&mdash;in medical language TUSSIS CONVULSIVA, or PERTUSSIS.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. In the beginning chiefly there is a dry cough, in which there is not thrown up any, or a very &s;mall quantity of thin &s;erum, more or le&s;s acrid&mdash;&s;ometimes the cough is moi&s;t, and then a blacki&s;h or blue mucus, often extremely tenacious, is evacuated&mdash;at the &s;ame time, the extremities grow cold&mdash;the bowels are co&s;tive&mdash;the urine is thin&mdash;and the blood is forced up copiou&s;ly, and with great force, into the &s;uperior parts, brea&s;t and head; from whence, during the fit, the face grows turgid with blood&mdash;the veins &s;well&mdash;the arteries beat &s;tronger and quicker&mdash;the eyes appear prominent&mdash;the tears <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;the eye-lids puff up&mdash;and &s;ometimes the blood, particu|larly if a &s;neezing comes on, is forced out from the no&s;trils&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">times the ve&s;&s;els of the lungs are ruptured, and there ari&s;es <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">itting of blood&mdash;a hiccough often accompanies it, and very <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> vomiting.&mdash;With re&s;pect to the convul&s;ive affection, it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not appear generally till the &s;econd or third week from the attack; 'till that time, it appears like a common cough, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> then it comes on at different times of the day, and conti|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> till &s;ome mucus is thrown up by the lungs, or the contents <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the &s;tomach evacuated, and then it cea&s;es&mdash;when it has put <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the&s;e appearances, its time of continuance is uncertain; it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> go off in a few weeks, or remain &s;ome months.&mdash;Before <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ts come on there is &s;ome warning given, chiefly an unea&s;y <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in breathing, and children will at this time catch <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of any thing that is near them, in order to &s;upport them|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">ves during the fit of coughing, which they dread.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> there are &s;ome ca&s;es where this ari&s;es from a peculiar in|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">on, that appears only like a common catarrh&mdash;&s;till it is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> commonly, indeed, almo&s;t always, with a peculiar kind of and, different in different ca&s;es, during &s;ome parts of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> called <HI>hooping,</HI> occa&s;ioned by many expirations being <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">vul&s;ively made, rapidly &s;ucceeding each other, whence a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> quantity of air mu&s;t be thrown out of the lungs; which <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="6 letters">&s;tance nece&s;&s;arily requires a full in&s;piration to &s;ucceed&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> this act the air ru&s;hes with unu&s;ual rapidity through the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> part of the windpipe, and occa&s;ions that particular <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, which forms the &s;triking and characteri&s;tic marks of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>Various have been the opinions of authors re&s;pecting the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of this di&s;ea&s;e&mdash;but if to what we have &s;aid, the occa&s;ional <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> accidental cau&s;es, which are apt to bring on the fit, be added, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> as violent exerci&s;e&mdash;full meals&mdash;food difficult of dige&s;tion&mdash;irritation
<PB N="442" REF="028021_0438_0FD67380F1192720">
of the lungs from &s;moke, du&s;t, or di&s;agreeable o|dours&mdash;&s;trong pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;or other con&s;iderable emotions of the mind&mdash;the relief occa&s;ioned by vomiting or expectoration of mucus freely, and the propen&s;ity to coughing being le&s;s when the &s;tomach is empty&mdash;we &s;hall not he&s;itate in concluding the lungs or the windpipe are the parts of the con&s;titution affected; and that predi&s;po&s;ition in the parts to feel the effects of peculiar infection form the immediate cau&s;es of the di&s;ea&s;e, and al&s;o au|thori&s;e us to &s;ay,</P>
<P>That the HOOPING-COUGH is a reiterated and violent concu&s;|&s;ion of the pulmonary organs, induced by the convul&s;ive action of the mu&s;cles of ribs, diaphragm, and belly, brought on by the &s;timulus of peculiar infection acting upon the lungs or windpipe, attended with a &s;en&s;e of &s;trangulation, repeated &s;ono|rous in&s;piration, and often with vomiting and expectoration.</P>
<P>CURE. The indications of which are, to correct or evacuate the peculiar infectious matter&mdash;to alleviate and le&s;&s;en the vio|lence and duration of the cough&mdash;and prevent tho&s;e mi&s;chiefs which are likely to ari&s;e in the habit, or parts of it, from its exce&s;s.</P>
<P>But as we know of no means either to correct or clear the con&s;titution of the morbid matter creating the di&s;ea&s;e, on the&s;e we can make no attempt&mdash;we mu&s;t therefore imitate nature in her efforts, by &s;uch means as experience, founded on the know|ledge of the laws of the animal oeconomy, will point out to us, in accompli&s;hing the two &s;ucceeding indications.</P>
<P>In full habits, therefore, if the face &s;wells much in cough|ing, looks red, and al&s;o the eyes, and other appearances of local plenitude &s;hew them&s;elves, bleeding is e&s;&s;entially u&s;eful; and this mu&s;t be repeated &s;o long as &s;uch appearances render it ne|ce&s;&s;ary&mdash;but this mu&s;t not be pu&s;hed too far; for then we &s;hould increa&s;e the convul&s;ive affection&mdash;hence, in the &s;lighter kinds of the di&s;ea&s;e it may be omitted&mdash;the body &s;hould be kept mo|derately open, not le&s;s than two or three &s;tools procured every day&mdash;violent purging, for the rea&s;on above recited, might be hurtful.</P>
<P>Gentle vomiting every day is beneficial in the forenoon, by &s;mall do&s;es of antimonials, one or two &s;poonfuls of the emetic mixture, (No. 11.) for a do&s;e, or as much as will produce the effect&mdash;and &s;hould any feveri&s;h &s;ymptoms attend, a quarter or half a grain of tartarized antimony may be given at night with the powder, (No. 2.) le&s;&s;ening or increa&s;ing the do&s;e according <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">o the con&s;titution; for this mode not only does good by the &s;hock it gives to the habit, a&s;&s;i&s;ting expectoration, and clearing the &s;tomach, but by determining the fluids to the &s;urface, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words">, and keeping the body open; which la&s;t if
<PB N="443" REF="028021_0439_0FD673AFF261EF18">
five mu&s;t be added&mdash;by per&s;i&s;ting in this mode, till evident &s;ymptoms of amendment pre&s;ented them&s;elves, then omitting the vomit to every &s;econd or third day, afterwards giving it once or twice a week, has been crowned with de&s;ired &s;ucce&s;s.</P>
<P>But, notwith&s;tanding, &s;hould &s;ymptoms appear indicative of an inflammatory tendency on the lungs, which will be &s;hewn by difficulty of breathing, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ever, and quick pul&s;e, where no cough|ing for &s;ome time has preceded, bli&s;ters then &s;hould be applied, particularly on the che&s;t.</P>
<P>Rubbing the pit of the &s;tomach, and down the &s;pine, with equal parts of rectified oil of amber and &s;pirits of wine, where there has been no inflammatory &s;ymptoms, or febrile tendency; or after the&s;e had gone off, has been con&s;idered of great u&s;e; but bleeding and purgatives, when nece&s;&s;ary, have preceded their u&s;e.</P>
<P>Small do&s;es of hemlock, (152.) have been given with appa|rent &s;ucce&s;s; and is by much the be&s;t among&s;t that cla&s;s &s;tiled &s;pecifics.</P>
<P>Towards the clo&s;e, where mucus appears vi&s;cid and difficult to expectorate, the ammoniacal mixture, (No. 141. 143.) is not an unprofitable medicine.</P>
<P>The &s;timulating tonic mixture, (No. 144.) has been &s;poken of with exaggerated prai&s;e, but I think too indi&s;criminately&mdash;early in the di&s;ea&s;e I would never recommend it, particular|ly in full habits with an inflammatory tendency&mdash;though in the latter &s;tages, where evacuants have preceded, I have given it with apparent advantage&mdash;and, perhaps, in weak, delicate con|&s;titutions, it may be exhibited at an earlier period, in &s;mall do&s;es two or three times a day, till a &s;light &s;trangury is excited&mdash;the do&s;e may either be dimini&s;hed, or given at longer inter|vals.</P>
<P>However, in the general mode of management, I &s;hould, in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> beginning, recommend vomiting and aperients, with bleed|ing, bli&s;tering, and u&s;e of antimonials, if nece&s;&s;ary&mdash;&s;mall do|&s;es of cicuta&mdash;and where no febrile &s;ymptoms declared them|&s;elves, external anti&s;pa&s;modics.</P>
<P>When the &s;ymptoms <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ad con&s;iderably abated, tonics, particu|larly bark, &s;hould &s;upply their place.</P>
<P>And, in the fir&s;t period, the diet &s;hould be ab&s;temious and &s;paring, as in inflammatory fever, if the &s;ymptoms ran high.&mdash;In the &s;econd, the mode of living &s;hould be more generous&mdash;and &s;hould the lungs be weakened by the violence of the di&s;|ea&s;e, a cour&s;e of a&s;s' milk, riding exerci&s;e, pure, clear air, and the u&s;e of bark, would be proper.&mdash;Indeed, in &s;ome ca&s;es,
<PB N="444" REF="028021_0440_0FD6738279143690">
change of air is highly nece&s;&s;ary, and very often alone produces the mo&s;t &s;alutary con&s;equences.</P>
<P>We mu&s;t ob&s;erve here, that often, when the coughing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">it is over, the patients are almo&s;t always perfectly relieved; but &s;hould they not, and the difficulty of breathing &s;hould continue, and there be any con&s;iderable febrile affections, there is danger, which mu&s;t ever be &s;u&s;pected; for few die but under the&s;e cir|cum&s;tances&mdash;now and then bringing on immediate &s;uffocation, and &s;ometimes con&s;umption&mdash;and often attended with extreme|ly trouble&s;ome and painful affections; but it will &s;ometimes occur in &s;o mild a &s;tate, that all fear is unnece&s;&s;ary&mdash;and this will manife&s;t it&s;elf by the gentlene&s;s of the &s;ymptoms; for though the complaint &s;hould be completely exi&s;ting, accom|panied with its certain &s;ymptoms of convul&s;ive cough and hooping, if the&s;e &s;hould be moderate, and their returns ob&s;erve di&s;tant periods&mdash;if the ejection of mucus from the lungs &s;hould be in no great degree&mdash;the difficulty of breathing and febrile affections do not manife&s;t them&s;elves&mdash;and between the fits the patient pre&s;erves his common habits of health, and the &s;ymp|toms gradually decrea&s;e, nature will be her own phy&s;ician&mdash;in the&s;e ca&s;es little is nece&s;&s;ary to be done.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 3. ASTHMA.</HEAD>
<P>from the Greek word <HI>ao</HI> vel <HI>aemai,</HI> anhelo, to breathe with difficulty. Though authors have divided this di&s;ea&s;e into dif|ferent &s;pecies they may all properly come under one head, con|&s;idering them, as they truly are, the &s;ame, only differently cir|cum&s;tanced; or ari&s;ing from other di&s;ea&s;es in the habit, and merely &s;ymptomatic; we &s;hall therefore con&s;ider them under one head, as a&s;thma in its different &s;tates, whether periodical, continual, or acute.&mdash;If the difficulty of breathing returns pe|riodically, it is termed ASTHMA&mdash;if it is chronic or continual, DYSPNAEA, from the Greek word <HI>dys,</HI> difficulter, and <HI>pueo,</HI> &s;piro, to breathe&mdash;if it is acute and violent, comes on &s;uddenly, and &s;oon terminates, and returns not again, ORTHOPNAEA, from <HI>or|thos,</HI> rectus, upright, and <HI>pueo,</HI> &s;piro, becau&s;e the patients can only breathe in an erect po&s;ture.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. Before the difficulty of breathing comes on, patients complain of a tightne&s;s in the region of the &s;tomach, which is di&s;tended, and wind pa&s;&s;es in con&s;iderable quantity up|wards&mdash;they then begin to be hot&mdash;are heavy and dull, complain of a pain of their head, are &s;ick, and make a quantity of pale urine, their &s;pirits become depre&s;&s;ed, the lungs feel a degree <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> inactivity and &s;tiffne&s;s&mdash;the brea&s;t is more than commonly load|ed&mdash;they
<PB N="445" REF="028021_0441_0FD673B1E2BEC298">
grow hoar&s;e, are &s;ick, breathe with great difficulty&mdash;and experience almo&s;t univer&s;ally a kind of &s;tupor, from the contracted &s;tate of the che&s;t, in&s;piration and expiration are per|formed &s;lowly&mdash;and, indeed, &s;o unea&s;y are they in the execution, that they elevate their &s;houlders, and extend their necks, in or|der to get relief in their manner of breathing&mdash;very frequently they vomit materials of different kinds&mdash;&s;ometimes vi&s;cid &s;limy <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, &s;ometimes green or yellow bile&mdash;in the violence of the fit, they have a palpitation of the heart, a livid colour of the face, and feel as if they &s;hould be &s;uffocated&mdash;when the &s;pa&s;mo|dic con&s;triction remits, they &s;pit up vi&s;cid phlegm, which ta&s;tes differently, intermixed with which are black coloured &s;treaks&mdash;the urine now changes its colour to a deeper hue, and depo&s;its a &s;entiment&mdash;all the &s;ymptoms increa&s;e at night, and are wor&s;e in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ed&mdash;patients feel mo&s;t alleviation in the open air&mdash;as &s;oon, how|ever, as the paroxy&s;m goes totally off, the expectoration cea&s;es.</P>
<P>From this account, though conci&s;e, it appears, that whatever will impede the pa&s;&s;age of the air into, or the free circulation of blood through the lungs, either by affecting the lungs them&s;elves, or dimini&s;hing the capacity of the che&s;t, will produce this com|plaint&mdash;hence the <HI>remote</HI> or <HI>inducing</HI> CAUSES are, thick, den&s;e, foggy air&mdash;or air impregnated with noxious particles or vapours received into the lungs&mdash;the aperture of the glottis, (the narrow <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">it at the upper part of the windpipe.) being &s;o contracted, or clo&s;ed up, and the pa&s;&s;ages leading to it from the parts about the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> being much &s;welled, and the inve&s;ting membranes <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> over with a mucous or purulent exudation; or them&s;elves greatly thickened; or the aperture may be &s;hut by the mu&s;cles of the windpipe being affected with &s;pa&s;modic contractions, which is not &s;eldom the ca&s;e&mdash;accumulations of watery, puru|lent fluid collected in the cellular &s;ub&s;tance&mdash;earthy concretions, or &s;chirrous tubercles formed in the lymphatic glands di&s;per&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">rough them&mdash;tumours lying contiguous to, or adjoining the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;extraordinary quantities of fat collected in the che&s;t, particularly about the large blood-ve&s;&s;els&mdash;too copious &s;ecretion, or a deficiency of the mucous which lubricates the branches of th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> windpipe&mdash;blood i&s;&s;uing from the extremities of the arte|ries into the air ve&s;&s;els&mdash;by an over di&s;ten&s;ion of the blood-ve&s;&s;els in the lungs&mdash;&s;pa&s;modic affections or pain affecting the the mu&s;|cles de&s;tined for re&s;piration, e&s;pecially the diaphragm, (33)&mdash;&s;pa&s;modic contractions of the branches of the windpipe from in|ternal cau&s;es&mdash;collections of water, blood, and matter within the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the che&s;t, &s;wellings of the belly from drop&s;ical collec|tions, enlarged vi&s;cera, or from a foetus&mdash;and, indeed, from an unnatural &s;mall-formed che&s;t&mdash;&s;trong pa&s;&s;ions, old ulcers healed,
<PB N="446" REF="028021_0442_0FD6738570755988">
any accu&s;tomary or critical evacuation thrown back into the ha|bit&mdash;wounds of the diaphragm, with a variety of others&mdash;and according to the nature of the acting cau&s;es, &s;o &s;hall we find the nature of the di&s;ea&s;e&mdash;but as in a work of this kind we cannot go into the minute particulars, we &s;hall confine our&s;elves to two; of one or other of which almo&s;t all a&s;thmatic complaints con&s;i&s;t, <ABBR>viz.</ABBR> the <HI>humid</HI> and <HI>&s;pa&s;modic;</HI> or <HI>convul&s;ive.</HI></P>
<P>CHARACTERISTIC SIGNS. A difficulty of breathing, with &s;traightne&s;s of the che&s;t&mdash;&s;ometimes continual, at others periodic&mdash;and &s;ometimes acute, violent, and not &s;ubject to re|turn.</P>
<P>DISTINCTIONS. Such as are affected with the humid, or moi&s;t a&s;thma, are &s;eldom free from cough, and, before the acce&s;|&s;ion of the fit, they have &s;ome &s;igns indicating its approach, as languor&mdash;lo&s;s of appetite, oppre&s;&s;ion, a flatulent fullne&s;s of the &s;tomach&mdash;after the&s;e there comes on a violent difficulty of breath|ing&mdash;there is no certainty of the duration of the fit, as it is from a few hours to three, four, or more days&mdash;&s;till the &s;en&s;e of &s;uf|focation and difficulty of breathing is &s;o di&s;tre&s;&s;ing, that the pa|tients are &s;carce able to lie, &s;peak, or expectorate&mdash;yet an inflam|mation of the lungs &s;eldom &s;ucceeds the fit, notwith&s;tanding there appears &s;uch violence affecting that organ&mdash;as it terminates, the breathing begins to be more free&mdash;mucus is expectorated&mdash;the urine changes to a darker colour, and depo&s;its a copious &s;edi|ment.</P>
<P>From the humid a&s;thma, the dry or convul&s;ive is di&s;tingui&s;h|ed, from the &s;uddenne&s;s of the attack&mdash;a pain and cramp affect|ing &s;ome part of the brea&s;t, particularly if any part of the brea&s;t has been injured formerly by a wound or blow&mdash;from the vio|lence of the &s;ymptoms&mdash;but the mo&s;t certain &s;ign is &s;aid to be, if a convul&s;ion of any other part be pre&s;ent, or has preceded.</P>
<P>Indeed, both the&s;e &s;pecies may be con&s;idered, and not impro|perly, of the nervous cla&s;s; one having a&s;&s;ociated with it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> accumulation of vi&s;cid phlegm in the lungs, the other free from &s;uch a conge&s;tion.</P>
<P>CURE. In full &s;trong habits, in fits of the a&s;thma, bleeding may be had recour&s;e to; and, if the con&s;titution will bear it, and the continuance of the violence of &s;ymptoms require it, it may be repeated&mdash;but in tho&s;e which are delicate and debilitated, or far advanced in life, it is more judicious to omit it&mdash;as &s;oon as po&s;&s;ible afterwards, the gly&s;ter, (No. 26.) in which from a half to a whole dram of a&s;afoetida, or more, may be di&s;&s;olved, &s;hould be admini&s;tered&mdash;and if the&s;e do not in a &s;hort time prove ef|ficacious, a bli&s;ter &s;hould be applied between the &s;houlders.</P>
<P>Vomits &s;hould be admini&s;tered, (No. 11, 12. 38.) either will
<PB N="447" REF="028021_0443_0FD673B759D3E870">
an&s;wer the purpo&s;e; but not till expectoration comes on with &s;ome degree of freedom; for, in the height of the fit, they might produce mi&s;chief, by creating too great an accumulation of blood in the head, and occa&s;ion not only dangerous, but fatal &s;ymp|toms&mdash;indeed, if the &s;tomach is loaded with any kind of foul|ne&s;s, vomiting will often prevent the a&s;thmatic fit.</P>
<P>A &s;trong infu&s;ion of roa&s;ted coffee has been known to allevi|ate the fit.</P>
<P>In order to promote expectoration, emetics &s;hould from time to time be given, and compo&s;itions formed of the attenuating gums, (No. 141. 143. 145)</P>
<P>Garlic is u&s;eful, (165) or extract of tobacco, (153.) is &s;uppo&s;ed to be capable of being &s;o managed as to exceed all the re&s;t of our medicines for this purpo&s;e: for tobacco chewed by tho&s;e unu&s;ed to it till it has brought on &s;ickne&s;s, and then going to bed to &s;weat; afterwards repeating it, has, we are told, cured the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>Squills, (176.) mixed with other expectorants, (164, 165.) increa&s;e their power, or are them&s;elves active; and al&s;o &s;oap mix|ed with the gums before mentioned.</P>
<P>And in all ca&s;es where the body is co&s;tive it &s;hould be kept gently open; for which purpo&s;e the pills, (No. 108, 109.) may be u&s;ed.</P>
<P>If opiates dare be admini&s;tered in the humid a&s;thma, they &s;hould always be c<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">pled with expectorants and volatiles&mdash;to which end, drops of opiated tincture and &s;alt of hart&s;horn may be added to the foetid attenuant mixture, (No. 145.) for the&s;e may prevent the opiates from making the mucus too vi&s;cid, or hindering expectoration from going on.</P>
<P>Diuretics are al&s;o beneficial, particularly in tho&s;e who have an acrimonious &s;tate of fluids.</P>
<P>Though very great caution is nece&s;&s;ary in the humid a&s;thma <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> our exhibition of opium, yet in the &s;pa&s;modic &s;pecies it may be given with more freedom; though it &s;hould be joined with &s;uch aperients as will keep the body open.</P>
<P>Cold bathing in an artificial &s;alt bath, or in the &s;ea, which is the mo&s;t eligible and certain, has proved efficacious in tho&s;e a&s;th|mas where, from the predi&s;po&s;ition in the lungs to become ir|ritable from &s;light cau&s;es, this complaint was brought on, except &s;ome peculiar circum&s;tances forbid the u&s;e, as tubercles, drop&s;y of the che&s;t, ulcers in the lungs, &amp;c. &amp;c.</P>
<P>Some have been &s;aid to die &s;uddenly from &s;uffocation in this di&s;ea&s;e; but this has generally been found to be from polypus in the lungs&mdash;partial pal&s;y, or &s;ome &s;pecies of drop&s;y, has been its termination.</P>
<P><PB N="448" REF="028021_0444_0FD6738A62EDF0B8">
I&s;&s;ues in both &s;pecies are recommended in the in&s;ide of the thighs ju&s;t above the knee.</P>
<P>Light diet, ea&s;ily dige&s;tible, and not flatulent, is the mo&s;t pro|per, and riding on hor&s;eback ought not to be di&s;pen&s;ed with becau&s;e it is always extremely beneficial.</P>
<P>With re&s;pect to &s;ituation, the patients ought to be left to them|&s;elves, and fix in that in which they are mo&s;t lively and comfor|table, and wherein they can breathe with the greate&s;t freedom&punc; for I have known the air of London more &s;alutary to &s;ome than the pure&s;t in the country.</P>
<P>Tho&s;e of &s;anguine habits, with &s;traight che&s;ts, who have been &s;ubject to frequent coughs, are mo&s;t liable, in the latter part of life, to fall into a&s;thmatic complaints, particularly if they are gro&s;s and fat&mdash;and it rages more in &s;ummer and autumn, than in the winter.</P>
<P>We &s;hall find, by the enumeration of the remote cau&s;es, this complaint may be the con&s;equence of others, and is it&s;elf, there|fore, purely &s;ymptomatic&mdash;to the original di&s;order we are to advert, at the &s;ame time that we u&s;e modes proper for the alle|viation of this di&s;tre&s;&s;ing &s;ymptom.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 4. SUFFOCATING CATARRH&mdash;CATARRHUS SUFFOCATIVUS.</HEAD>
<P>We mu&s;t be careful not to confound this with the TRACHAEAL QUINSY, or CROUP, (p. 317, 320,) becau&s;e &s;ome authors have given the &s;ame name to this: notwith&s;tanding, we &s;hall find them widely different, and that they require different modes of cure&mdash;<HI>that</HI> being an inflammatory affection of the branches of the windpipe, requires bleeding, which might be highly &s;erviceable&mdash;<HI>this</HI> being &s;pa&s;modic, bleeding would be as injurious.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. In this complaint there is a peculiar kind of &s;hrill croaking, accompanied with a quick and difficult breath|ing, attacking violently and &s;uddenly, and generally in the night&mdash;from the &s;ingular noi&s;e, we may ea&s;ily di&s;tingui&s;h it from inflammatory affections of the lungs, which never attends them, and always makes its approach more gradually.</P>
<P>CHARACTERISTIC SIGNS. A &s;uffocation ari&s;ing from a &s;pa&s;modic con&s;triction of the lungs, or rather windpipe, or a &s;pa&s;m of the diaphragm, without hy&s;teric affections.</P>
<P>CURE. We mu&s;t here endeavour to take off the &s;pa&s;modic affections as &s;oon as po&s;&s;ible, by bli&s;tering the back, and the co|pious u&s;e of a&s;a foetida, giving gly&s;ters of a &s;olution of this gum, and pouring the &s;ame down the throat: and if the fit a|bates, or is conquered by the&s;e means, bark mu&s;t be given free|ly, to prevent a return.</P>
<P><PB N="449" REF="028021_0445_0FD673B946B90DD8">
To a child eighteen months old, &s;ome have given an ounce of a&s;a foetida in &s;olution, and injected as much by gly&s;ters, in the &s;pace of forty eight-hours.&mdash;In &s;o &s;hort a time it will probably be very difficult to get a child &s;o young to &s;wallow &s;o large a quantity.</P>
<P>However, in &s;maller do&s;es it has been equally efficacious&mdash;alternate do&s;es of mu&s;k and a&s;a foetida will an&s;wer the purpo&s;e, in conjunction with the gly&s;ter.</P>
<P>This di&s;ea&s;e is often met with in children, and is in &s;ome &s;ea|&s;ons epidemical&mdash;but it very frequently proves &s;o &s;uddenly mor|tal, that medical a&s;&s;i&s;tance is of &s;mall con&s;equence.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 5. SPURIOUS PERIPNEUMONY&mdash;PERIPNEUMONIA N<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">THA.</HEAD>
<P>from the Greek word <HI>nothos,</HI> &s;purius.</P>
<P>There have been different opinions concerning the &s;eat of this complaint, though all agree re&s;pecting the affection of the lungs, yet differ with re&s;pect to the part&mdash;&s;ome a&s;&s;ert that it is the &s;mall branches of the pulmonary arteries, and tho&s;e of the wind|pipe&mdash;others, that it is in the cellular &s;ub&s;tance of that organ, that is, the membrane which connects together all the parts of which the lungs are formed, and is the &s;ame connecting medi|um which unites the &s;malle&s;t fibres of the body with each other|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ungs and Cellular Membrane.</P>
<P>I confe&s;s my&s;elf of the latter opinion; for, though expectora|tion has been carried on freely in this complaint, the patients notwith&s;tanding have died, which is not the ca&s;e in humoral a&s;th|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">, or the inflammatory peripneumony, where the air ve&s;&s;els, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the &s;mall branches of the pulmonary artery, have been affect|ed; for, under the&s;e circum&s;tances, the lungs have an opportu|nity of freeing them&s;elves from the oppre&s;&s;ive load, by the free <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">munication tho&s;e parts have with the windpipe&mdash;whil&s;t, on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> hand, in order to form a cure, the offending matter mu&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ufficiently to be re-ab&s;orbed by the lymphatics, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> back into the cour&s;e of circulation. We have thought it nece&s;&s;ary to premi&s;e thus much, in order to furni&s;h a perfect <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the complaint, which, we think, will farther be corrob|orated by the &s;ymptoms and con&s;equences.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. In this complaint, though there are chill|ne&s;s and heat alternating with each other, yet neither is the heat, pain, or thir&s;t, in any great degree&mdash;the pul&s;e is frequent, weak, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;mall&mdash;it is often attended with, or there is a &s;trong propen|&s;ity to; vomiting&mdash;giddine&s;s or pain affects the head&mdash;the pati|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ugh, and experience a &s;en&s;e of weight in the brea&s;t, with a difficulty of breathing, and tightne&s;s within the che&s;t&mdash;and,
<PB N="450" REF="028021_0446_0FD6738B8783C848">
for the mo&s;t part, the urine is of a pale colour&mdash;in &s;ome ca&s;es they expectorate tolerably freely; but even then the difficulty of breathing abates not, but they &s;till wheeze and feel them|&s;elves oppre&s;&s;ed; and, when that is the ca&s;e, we mu&s;t be very careful not to progno&s;ticate too favourably; for the fatal cau&s;e &s;till exi&s;ts, and mo&s;t commonly terminates in death.</P>
<P>CAUSES. An accumulation of &s;erum in the cellular &s;ub&s;tance of the lungs&mdash;hence ari&s;es great oppre&s;&s;ion on the air ve&s;&s;els, and &s;ome &s;light ob&s;truction on the pulmonary and bronchial arteries, thereby hindering a full and free circulation of the blood through the &s;ub&s;tance of the lungs&mdash;to which old people, tho&s;e who a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> phlegmatic, weak, relaxed, and fat, are mo&s;t &s;ubject&mdash;and the&s;e it attacks mo&s;t frequently in moi&s;t, foggy, and rainy &s;ea&s;ons.</P>
<P>CURE. The indications are, to di&s;lodge the contaminated &s;erum, and throw it out of the con&s;titution, by making it &s;uf|ficiently thin, &s;o that it may be ab&s;orbed from the cells where it is lodged&mdash;and this we mu&s;t attempt by emetics and &s;timulants; for on the&s;e we can alone depend for &s;aving the life of the patient.</P>
<P>The antimonial emetics are the mo&s;t proper, (No. 11, 12.) given in &s;uch a manner that the &s;hock and agitation may be mo&s;t powerful&mdash;hence admini&s;tered on the &s;tomach being empty, or nearly &s;o&mdash;the arms, back, &s;ides, and legs &s;hould be fomented, and bli&s;ters applied to them&mdash;mu&s;tard whey, (No. 127.) decoc|tion of &s;eneka root, (179.) have been thought u&s;eful&mdash;when the cough has been violent, gentle opiates, joined with aloetics, have been admitted&mdash;volatile &s;aline mixture, (No. 126) coupled with nau&s;eating do&s;es of antimonials, in order to promote expectora|tion, have been advi&s;ed, and may, perhaps, be u&s;eful to remove ob&s;tructions formed in the &s;mall branches of the blood-ve&s;&s;els of the lungs, occa&s;ioned by the external pre&s;&s;ure of &s;erum collected in the cellular &s;ub&s;tance; but they touch not the grand cau&s;e; for though the&s;e, or the application of &s;ome of the attenuating medicines, &s;uch as camphor, vinegar of &s;quills, gum ammoniac, may cau&s;e expectoration; in &s;pite of all our endeavours, we ve|ry often, indeed, mo&s;t commonly, &s;ee death u&s;hered in, by a per|petual laborious wheezing&mdash;great re&s;tle&s;&s;ne&s;s and anxiety, into|lerable oppre&s;&s;ion at the pit of the &s;tomach&mdash;a con&s;tant drow&s;y di&s;po&s;ition&mdash;coldne&s;s of the hands and feet, and a livid co|lour of them as well as the face, owing to the blood there &s;tag|nating.</P>
<P>In phlegmatic and relaxed habits, i&s;&s;ues on the in&s;ide of the thigh above the knee may act as a preventive, by hindering a &s;erous accumulation taking place in the cellular &s;ub&s;tance of the lungs, by affording a continual drain to the con&s;titution; but in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">it of the di&s;ea&s;e, though advi&s;ed by &s;ome, can afford no re|lief,
<PB N="451" REF="028021_0447_0FD76EB09A3820B0">
from the &s;lowne&s;s of their action. The body &s;hould always be kept open by gly&s;ters, whatever mode we pur&s;ue; and we may venture to a&s;&s;ert, that if emetics, bli&s;ters, and the u&s;e of volatiles, will not afford relief, medicine cannot be of much &s;er|vice.</P>
<P>We mu&s;t be very careful in di&s;tingui&s;hing this from the true peripneumony, which may be readily done by remembering, notwith&s;tanding there may be &s;ome &s;imilar appearances, that <HI>in the &s;purious peripneumony there is no acute fever</HI>&mdash;add al&s;o from the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ASTHMA, becau&s;e that is never attended with any fever; in this a &s;light fever manife&s;tly &s;hews it&s;elf, though far more ob&s;cure <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in the inflammatory peripneumony.</P>
<P>We &s;hould have ob&s;erved, that in all di&s;ea&s;es where a cough appears to be a prevailing &s;ymptom, mucilaginous and oily com|po&s;itions are freely exhibited&mdash;here though they mu&s;t be avoid|ed, as mu&s;t al&s;o opiates, except under circum&s;tances which we have before &s;pecified.</P>
