<DIV1 N="19" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>SECTION XIX.</HEAD>
<P>WE now come to &s;peak of tho&s;e di&s;ea&s;es wherein the humours of the machine are particularly concerned, owing to &s;ome <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in point of quantity, or quality, or both, wherein they de|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="5 letters"> from their natural &s;tate, and from thence produce a varie|ty of di&s;ea&s;es&mdash;the fir&s;t of which we &s;hall &s;pecify is</P>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. JAUNDICE;</HEAD>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the French word jaune, yellow&mdash;it is al&s;o called ICTERUS, from the Greek <HI>ikteros,</HI> aurugo vel aurigo, which name it bears, from the appearance of yellowne&s;s like gold&mdash;MORBUS REGIUS&mdash;MORBUS ARQUATUS&mdash;SUFFUSIO BILIS, from bile being &s;uffu&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the habit&mdash;this, therefore, is con&s;idered as a di&s;ea&s;e produc|ed by the bile either ob&s;tructing the common duct of the gall <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">dder, called ductus communis choledochus, (36.) by its vi&s;|cidity, or concreting into a hard &s;ub&s;ta<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ee, named gall-&s;tones&mdash;though it may be produced by other di&s;ea&s;es, as we &s;hall &s;ee in the enumeration of its remote cau&s;es.</P>
<P>But we here mean only to &s;peak of it as originating from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cau&s;es above &s;pecified, the re&s;t being properly con&s;idered <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> as &s;ymptomatic, and mu&s;t have applications accordingly.</P>
<P><PB N="452" REF="028021_0448_0FD673F24428D1C0">
DESCRIPTION. At the commencement the patients gene|rally appear languid and indolent, with an unea&s;y &s;en&s;ation of tightne&s;s and oppre&s;&s;ive weight at the pit of the &s;tomach&mdash;af|ter this there comes on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;light yellowne&s;s at the angles of the eyes, which di&s;per&s;es it&s;elf over the white, the &s;kin at the &s;ame time putting on a &s;imilar appearance&mdash;there is very often a pain of the &s;tomach&mdash;the body becomes co&s;tive&mdash;the appetite fails&mdash;the excrements appear of a clay or a&s;h colour&mdash;and the urine yellow, tinging any white linen immer&s;ed in it of the &s;ame colour, and depo&s;iting a copious yellow coloured &s;ediment&mdash;there is generally a weight, fullne&s;s, and &s;tretching of the right &s;ide under the &s;purious ribs&mdash;there is al&s;o a general nau|&s;ea and loathing of food, &s;ometimes attended with vomiting&mdash;the &s;kin often itches&mdash;the pul&s;e is &s;ometimes quick&mdash;&s;ometimes there is a hiccough&mdash;and, &s;hould a loo&s;ene&s;s come on, with yel|low coloured faeces, the di&s;ea&s;e terminates.&mdash;The&s;e are <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> common &s;ymptoms, and this the common cour&s;e of the curable jaundice, which will go off in a few days, if it has originated only from a con&s;triction of the duodenum, or the common g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ll duct&mdash;nor will it continue much longer if vi&s;cid bile has only been the ob&s;tructing cau&s;e&mdash;but if biliary concretions have been the &s;ource, in a few weeks, or months, mo&s;t probably the &s;ame &s;ymptoms will make their appearance in the &s;ame &s;ucce&s;&s;ion; and, at length, the di&s;ea&s;e will, from a repetition become per|petual&mdash;&s;ometimes better and wor&s;e, though le&s;s &s;evere than <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> fir&s;t.</P>
<P>Under the&s;e circum&s;tances, the yellow colour becomes deep|er in a great degree, forming what is called the black jaundice&mdash;&s;o much does the bile diffu&s;e it&s;elf through every part of the habit, <HI>that it has been a&s;&s;erted,</HI> objects appear to &s;uch patients of a yellow colour; and even the &s;aliva acquires a bitter ta&s;te&mdash;however, in the&s;e ca&s;es, the blood &s;eems to be &s;o &s;urcharged with bile, that its texture is broken down&mdash;frequent haemor|rhages appear, particularly of the no&s;e; and the blood tran&s;ud|ing al&s;o through the &s;ides of the ve&s;&s;els is depo&s;ited in the cellu|lar connecting membrane, occa&s;ioning a general livid ca&s;t&mdash;the fluids then running into a thin acrimonious &s;tate, occa&s;ions great itching&mdash;the body becomes drop&s;ical&mdash;the belly fills with water; and thus is the mi&s;erable &s;cene clo&s;ed.</P>
<P>CAUSES. The <HI>remote</HI> or <HI>inducing</HI> are, bilious or hy&s;teric co|lic&mdash;&s;trongly operating purges&mdash;o&s;&s;ification, or compre&s;&s;ion of the biliary ducts, from tumours externally or internally &s;ituat|ed&mdash;pregnancy&mdash;violent anger, or long continued grief&mdash;ob|&s;truction, &s;cirrhus, or ab&s;ce&s;s of the liver&mdash;that black coloured vi&s;cid fluid in the inte&s;tines of new born or young infants, call|ed
<PB N="453" REF="028021_0449_0FD673BE16C85620">
meconium, being not properly purged off&mdash;intermittent fe|vers taken off too &s;oon by the u&s;e of the bark&mdash;gall &s;tones or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, or vi&s;cid bile, ob&s;tructing the gall duct.</P>
<P>The <HI>proximate</HI> or <HI>immediate,</HI> an ab&s;orption of bile, which has <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;eparated, into the habit&mdash;&s;ome are of opinion, that bile mu&s;t be &s;ecreted and thrown back into the fluids before a jaun|dice <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cake place&mdash;whil&s;t others hold, that an increa&s;ed quan|tity of bile not &s;ecreted into the gall bladder, by its vi&s;cidity <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> may al&s;o be the cau&s;e&mdash;however, it is not our bu|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="6 letters"> here to attempt to &s;ettle the&s;e doubts&mdash;our opinion will <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> known by the following.</P>
<P>CHARACTERISTIC SIGNS. A partial or total ob&s;truc|tion of the ductus communis choledochus, (36.) mo&s;t commonly <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> vi&s;cid or concreted bile, attended with a yellow colour of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> white of the eyes and &s;kin&mdash;high coloured urine, tinging <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> dipt into it of a yellow colour.</P>
<P>CURE. The indications of cure are, to remove the ob&s;truc|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">; which, as it originates from different cau&s;es, will require <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> modes of treatment.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> it &s;hould ari&s;e from vi&s;cid bile, which we take to be the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> common cau&s;e, in full habits, bleeding may fir&s;t be had <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to, and afterwards dandelion draughts may be given, (No. 149.) every night and morning, for two or three &s;ucce&s;|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> days; then the &s;aponacious pills, (No. 150.) four, two or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> times a day, with four &s;poonfuls of the &s;aline mixture, (No. 1.) or infu&s;ion of qua&s;&s;ia, (175.) or dandelion tea,&mdash;after <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> have been continued for &s;ix or &s;even days, if no &s;igns of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> appear, if the yellow colour of the &s;kin and eyes <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not to grow thinner, the urine to be of a lighter tinge, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> there &s;hould be no yellowne&s;s in the &s;tools, an emetic, (No. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">) then will be proper, which may be often repeated, if <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; and the day after the calomel bolus and purging <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, (No. 105, 106.)&mdash;&s;ome indeed advi&s;e &s;mall do&s;es of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, (No. 109.) to be mixed with the &s;aponaceous pills, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> purged off occa&s;ionally&mdash;in addition to what is here advi&s;|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> fomentations, (No. 85.) may be applied frequently to the right &s;ide, or bags of hot &s;alt, oats, or a bladder half filled with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> bran and water, pretty warm; and, by proceeding in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> way, there is little doubt but the vi&s;cid bile will be remo|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">, and the cau&s;e of the di&s;ea&s;e conquered.</P>
<P>But &s;hould there be any acute pain attendant in the region of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> liver with a quickne&s;s of the pul&s;e, and other &s;ymptoms <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of any inflammatory affections, we mu&s;t proceed as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in inflammation of that organ, (340.) before we have <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to any emetic, which may &s;afely be admini&s;tered <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the inflammatory or painful &s;ymptoms are &s;ubdued.</P>
<P><PB N="454" REF="028021_0450_0FD673F58E077228">
Towards the conclu&s;ion o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the di&s;ea&s;e, and to prevent a re|lap&s;e, the aromatic bitter bolus, (No. 64.) or the deob&s;truent &s;oap pills, (No. 117.) may be continued for &s;ome time twice a day, wa&s;hed down with chamomile tea, or infu&s;ion of qua&s;&s;ia, (175.)</P>
<P><HI>Bath</HI> and <HI>Harrowgate</HI> waters have been by &s;ome con&s;idered as &s;pecific&mdash;they may certainly be very u&s;eful in jaundice pr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">|ceeding from vi&s;cid bile, or bilious infarction of the liver, to|wards the conclu&s;ion of the complaint, and calculated perfectly to clear the liver from the&s;e cau&s;es; but in other ca&s;es would, from their heating and &s;timulating powers, be highly impro|per.</P>
<P>When it proceeds from gall-&s;tones, or &s;cirrho&s;ity of the li|ver, we mu&s;t act as in ca&s;es of pain in that organ from the&s;e cau&s;es. (3<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">1.)</P>
<P>When from a redundancy of bile, and bilious colic, what has been recommended in tho&s;e complaints, (356, &amp;c. will <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> proper.)</P>
<P>In order, however, to prevent a return, and invigorate <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> part of the &s;y&s;tem particularly affected, the diet of our patients &s;hould be light and ea&s;y of dige&s;tion, avoiding all fatty or vi&s;|cid &s;ub&s;tances, or things too powerfully a&s;tringent: the body &s;hould be kept regularly open, by the occa&s;ional exhibition of the aperient pills, (No. 108, 109.)&mdash;riding exerci&s;e &s;hould be per&s;evered in, and the place of re&s;idence &s;hould be &s;uch as af|forded a pure, light, clear air.</P>
<P>HOFFMAN, in curing this di&s;ea&s;e ari&s;ing from ob&s;truction, u&s;ed to begin with bleeding; afterwards pre&s;cribed half <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ounce of antimonial wine in one or two ounces of oil of al|monds, and ordered the patient to drink freely of the decoc|tion of the roots of &s;trawberries, mar&s;h-mallows, liquorice, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a handful of endive, &s;uccory, chickweed, chervil, beet, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;orrel&mdash;to each of which decoctions he added two drams <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">f cream of tartar and fifteen grains of nitre&mdash;in the evening <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> opening gly&s;ter was given, and afterwards, a purge of Ep&s;om &s;alt and &s;yrup of ro&s;es, of each an ounce, di&s;&s;olved in two or three ounces of water, or made with &s;enna and tamarinds&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the&s;e formed not a cure, to the acidulated chalybeate &s;prings he had recour&s;e.</P>
<P>Thirty grains of the aloetic pill, with myrrh occa&s;ionally, i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> a beneficial medicine.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="disease">
<HEAD>&sect; 2. DROPSY&mdash;HYDROPS;</HEAD>
<P>from the Greek word, <HI>udor</HI> aqua, water; becau&s;e this ari&s;es
<PB N="455" REF="028021_0451_0FD673BF42F75A88">
from a collection of lymph, or &s;erous fluid within the cellular membrane, or different cavities of the body.</P>
<P>When it is general, it is called ANASARCA, from <HI>ana,</HI> per, through, and <HI>&s;arx,</HI> caro, fle&s;h&mdash;when local, it receives its name from the part it affects, or the appearance it occa&s;ions.</P>
<P>If in the brea&s;t, it is called HYDROTHORAX, from <HI>udor,</HI> and <HI>tho|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"></HI> pectus, and che&s;t&mdash;if in the belly, ASCITES, from <HI>a&s;kos,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ter, a leathern bottle, from its appearance&mdash;if in the womb, HYDROMETRON, from <HI>udor,</HI> and <HI>metron,</HI> matrix, the womb&mdash;if in the head, HYDROCEPHALUS, from <HI>udor,</HI> and <HI>kephalos,</HI> caput the head&mdash;and other &s;pecies, as DROPSY OF THE LUNGS&mdash;OVARIA&mdash;FALLOPIAN TUBES&mdash;but as they all originate from one and the &s;ame proximate cau&s;e, when curable, they require &s;imilar internal modes for the accompli&s;hment.&mdash;We &s;hall therefore de|&s;cribe the &s;ymptoms by which they may be di&s;covered, before <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> proceed to the method to be adopted for their cure, making <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ob&s;ervations where the general rules may be deviated <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, with re&s;pect to the &s;ituation of the watery collection&mdash;and, FIRST, of</P>
<P>GENERAL DROPSY, or ANARSARCA&mdash;this is al&s;o called LEU|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">LEGMATIA, from <HI>leukos,</HI> albus, and <HI>phlegmatia,</HI> pituita, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the colourle&s;s &s;welling of the &s;kin, ari&s;ing from the col|lation of a watery or pituitous humour beneath.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. In this di&s;ea&s;e the body has a pale ap|pearance&mdash;the whole &s;kin grows &s;oft, with an inela&s;tic &s;welling&mdash;this originates from watery lymph copiou&s;ly diffu&s;ed through, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> accumulated in the cellular membrane, (25.) encircling the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> body, its mu&s;cles and coats&mdash;whence ari&s;es a &s;oft tumor, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and &s;qualid, over the whole of the machine, retaining the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">tation, or print of the finger, wherever &s;trongly impre&s;&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> feet and legs &s;well, particularly towards the evening, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">umefaction gradually a&s;cends upwards <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the whole <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> membrane&mdash;hence it differs from tha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> kind of pa&s;ty <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> which only affects the lower extremities in the evening <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ub&s;ide in the morning; for in the ana&s;arca, in the morning, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> parts are more &s;welled, particularly the eyelids and cheeks, al&s;o the &s;crotum, (53.) and penis, (53.)&mdash;a difficulty of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">thing comes on, and cough&mdash;the patients lo&s;e their appetite, but are very de&s;irous of liquids&mdash;the urine at fir&s;t is pale and watery, though in the latter &s;tages high coloured, though almo&s;t always &s;mall in quantity&mdash;the pul&s;e is &s;mall, quick, and irregu|lar&mdash;there is a &s;light fever&mdash;&s;leep affords little refre&s;hment&mdash;and they &s;eldom or never &s;weat.</P>
<P>ASCITES is a con&s;iderable &s;welling of the belly, with a per|ceptible fluctuation within; for if the hand be laid on one &s;ide,
<PB N="456" REF="028021_0452_0FD673F6B2C81B58">
and the other &s;truck, this fluctuation is readily di&s;covered. I<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the common &s;pecies of this complaint, before the belly appears to &s;well, the patients make water in very &s;mall quantity, which is foul, and depo&s;its a yellowi&s;h &s;ediment, or one coloured like brick-du&s;t&mdash;the legs generally &s;well, then the belly&mdash;after which a difficulty of breathing comes on, e&s;pecially upon lying down&mdash;the patients complain of weight or heavine&s;s&mdash;the fle&s;h wa&s;tes away&mdash;and the bowels are commonly co&s;tive&mdash;general debilty takes place&mdash;the pul&s;e becomes weak and frequent&mdash;there is a &s;low fever attends&mdash;by continuance the water become<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> putrid, and brings on inflammation, ulceration, and mortifica|tion of the vi&s;cera; for, on opening bodies who die of this com|plaint, &s;ome of them are &s;ound di&s;ea&s;ed, mo&s;t frequently th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> liver, next to that the &s;pleen, &s;weatbread, and me&s;enteric gland<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">.</P>
