<HEAD>&sect; 6. CANCER.</HEAD>
<P>This we may &s;ometimes trace from the foregoing di&s;ea&s;e; for it has been ob&s;erved, that &s;ome of tho&s;e who, in the early periods of their lives, have &s;hewn appearances of &s;crophula, have in the more advanced &s;tages been affected with cancers&mdash;hence it is not improbable but that there may be &s;ome affinity between the humours producing the&s;e two di&s;ea&s;es. It has been called CARSINOMA, from the Greek word <HI>karkinos,</HI> cancer, a crab, from its appearance, the turgid veins running round the margin of the tumors being &s;omething &s;imilar to crabs claws&mdash;and when a hard &s;cirrhous tumor begins to be unequal&mdash;puts on a livid colour&mdash;has acute darting pains &s;hooting through it&mdash;and at the &s;ame time veins &s;urrounding it being di&s;tended, and having a &s;erpentine appearance, called varico&s;e&mdash;the&s;e are &s;ymptoms con|&s;idered as declaratory of a cancer&mdash;but, indeed, &s;ometimes it will ari&s;e in the lips, gums, tongue, and &s;ome other parts of the body, without the appearance of &s;cirrhus preceding it.</P>
<P>When this tumor lurks under the &s;kin, it is called OCCULT&mdash;but when it becomes ulcerated, it then is called OPEN, and is di&s;tingui&s;hed by a very offen&s;ive and foetid di&s;charge&mdash;the lips of the ulcer inverted&mdash;an hardne&s;s of the &s;kin, an exudation of a
<PB N="476" REF="028021_0472_0FD674134259C2C8">
thin, acrimonious fluid&mdash;pricking, darting pain, very acute, and ob&s;tinate re&s;i&s;tance to every application.</P>
<P>Like &s;crophulous tumors cancerous ones are lumpy, unequal; but exceed the&s;e and every other &s;pecies of tumor in hardne&s;s, though, whil&s;t they remain in an indolent &s;tate, and without a|ny di&s;colouration in the &s;kin, they are termed SCIRRHI&mdash;when an itching is perceptible, &s;ucceeded by the darting pain we have before de&s;cribed, the &s;kin turns darki&s;h or livid, and the veins under the &s;kin put on a varico&s;e appearance (475.) in the part affected, they then are con&s;idered as CANCERS.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. A cancer in the beginning is generally &s;mall, and increa&s;es gradually; and notwith&s;tanding the changes of the colour of the &s;kin already mentioned, and that of becom|ing painful from being indolent, it is &s;ometimes very difficult to determine, when the tran&s;ition from one &s;tate to the other takes place, becau&s;e, according to concurring cau&s;es, the progre&s;s becomes quick or &s;low.</P>
<P>It has, with great judgment, been remarked, that <HI>when pecu|liar kinds of burning &s;hooting pains, an alteration of the colour of the &s;kin to that of browni&s;h, purple, or livid,</HI> appear, then the di&s;|ea&s;e may be con&s;idered as a malignant &s;cirrhus, or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cancer&mdash;and al&s;o when it is arrived to this &s;tate in women brea&s;ts, the magnitude of the tumor greatly increa&s;es, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> quickly, having a knotty, unequal &s;urface, a greater number of glands being ob&s;tructed, the nipple &s;inks in&mdash;full and turgid <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> con&s;picuous, diffu&s;ing them&s;elves &s;ome di&s;tance round the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and re&s;embling the claws of crabs.</P>
<P>The&s;e are deemed characteri&s;tic &s;igns of an occult cancer ex|ternally &s;ituated; but when the&s;e pains and heat &s;ucceed in parts where the patient has before been &s;en&s;ible of a weight and pre&s;|&s;ure, accompanied with a dull pain, we have great rea&s;on to be|lieve it lurks internally.</P>
<P>A cancer may remain in an indolent &s;tate for years, without any ulceration, yet the humour may acquire &s;uch a degree of acrimony as to erode the integuments, then commences the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cancer, from which will i&s;&s;ue a thin fluid of &s;o cau&s;tic a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that the neighbouring parts will be &s;peedily corroded, whether hard or &s;oft, and thus forms an ulcer &s;o ob&s;tinate, that it is in|capable of being healed by any applications yet di&s;covered, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> can the acrimony be corrected or &s;ubdued by any known <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="5 letters">|ative&mdash;the fle&s;h within the ulcer becomes &s;pongy&mdash;the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> the wound &s;welled, livid, and inverted&mdash;the pain <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> glands of the neighbouring parts become <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> haemorrhages en&s;ue, the appetite is lo&s;t&mdash;a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of the fle&s;h, comes on&mdash;the &s;trength fails, the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> are af|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">cted
<PB N="477" REF="028021_0473_0FD673D745F2DB90">
with convul&s;ions and &s;wooning&mdash;and death, more de&s;ira|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e than life, clo&s;es the mi&s;erable &s;cene.</P>
<P>CAUSES. The <HI>remote</HI> or <HI>inducing</HI> are &s;aid to be, &s;uppre&s;&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">vacuations&mdash;great dejection of &s;pirits&mdash;frights and anger&mdash;a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of living, medicines, or other di&s;ea&s;es generating a cor|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&s;ive acrimony in the blood&mdash;an increa&s;ed motion in the blood, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> whatever cau&s;e it may ari&s;e, cold, external irritation from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, compre&s;&s;ion, ery&s;ipelas, or medical &s;ub&s;tances&mdash;barren|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e&s;s, and a life of celibacy; for women who have lived in that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, as well as arriving at the period of men&s;trual ce&s;&s;ation, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> mo&s;t liable to this complaint&mdash;next to tho&s;e, mothers who <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not &s;uckled&mdash;afterwards, tho&s;e who are pa&s;t child-bear|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ng, and tho&s;e who are lea&s;t &s;ubject to the di&s;order, are men, and women who have rai&s;ed their own children by the brea&s;t.</P>
<P>The <HI>proximate</HI> or <HI>immediate</HI> is &s;uppo&s;ed to be, a &s;pecific cor|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ption or putrefaction, though &s;low in its progre&s;s, of the hu|mours ob&s;tructing the glands.</P>
<P>CURE. A true cancer, I believe, is &s;eldom or ever cured, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> by amputating the part affected&mdash;if, therefore, the com|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">int is in its recent &s;tate, &s;mall, &s;olitary, and moveable&mdash;<HI>e&s;pe|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">lly if it comes from an external injury</HI>&mdash;if it is in a free &s;itua|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">, neither adhering to any large ve&s;&s;els, nerves, ligaments, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to the bones&mdash;the con&s;titution being good, and in young &s;ubjects; the part affected may be taken off by the knife; and this mode is preferable to the application of any cau&s;tic &s;ub|&s;tances&mdash;but, in all the&s;e ca&s;es, where operations are to be per|formed, or external applications made u&s;e of, the be&s;t advice <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> can give is, for the patients to depend on the judgment of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> cautious and experienced &s;urgeon.</P>
<P>With regard to medical a&s;&s;i&s;tance in tho&s;e &s;cirrhous tumors, before they have put on the po&s;itive appearance of cancer, ex|perience authori&s;es us to recommend bleeding, to take off the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> fullne&s;s of the habit&mdash;afterwards the application of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ches to the part affected, and that repeated, as occa&s;ion may <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and now and then exhibiting a cooling purgative&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, where we are led to believe there may be a cancerous <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">dency, from &s;ome degree and continuance of pain, topical <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is nece&s;&s;ary, and the application of poultices made <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">emlock leaves, with the internal exhibition of the &s;ame <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, (152.) in extract of powder, has apparently &s;topped <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> progre&s;s of the complaint. Indeed, in the&s;e three ca&s;es of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the uterus, by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> proper management of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> corro&s;ive &s;ublimate, opium, and &s;ome ar&s;enical prepara|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">. I have known great benefit to be derived&mdash;one of which, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> mo&s;t violent, occurred at Knight&s;bridge lately, when I at|tended
<PB N="478" REF="028021_0474_0FD6741516130810">
with Mr. Williams, an attentive and judicious practition|er, the patient was a per&s;on of delicate habit, &s;ubject to hy&s;teric affections, from &s;trong nervous incitability, and who&s;e mu&s;cular &s;y&s;tem was al&s;o more than commonly irritable&mdash;&s;he complain|ed of excruciating pain in the lower part of the belly&mdash;her pul&s;e was quick, &s;kin dry, totally re&s;tle&s;s, and very thir&s;ty, &s;he now and then complained of chillne&s;s, which was always &s;uc|ceeded by a heat of the &s;kin, and a quickne&s;s of the pul&s;e, that always increa&s;ed towards evening, and went off by copious per|&s;piration, the womb was apparently much enlarged, very hard, and pre&s;&s;ed low down into the pelvis, &s;he complained of pains darting through the lower part of the belly, and, from the weight and pain was altogether incapable of walking, nor could be moved from her bed without great agony&mdash;whatever &s;he took for &s;ome time &s;he vomited up, &s;o that &s;he received, for the &s;pace of three weeks, little or no nouri&s;hment&mdash;&s;he was al&s;o often and &s;trongly affected with that unplea&s;ant &s;en&s;e of &s;uf|focation, or choaking, from the contraction of the throat, called globus hy&s;tericus&mdash;&s;he had al&s;o through the vagina a very of|fen&s;ive and acrimonious di&s;charge, which, from excoriating the parts, occa&s;ioned her much additional unea&s;ine&s;s, however, by the u&s;e of hemlock, corro&s;ive &s;ublimate, and a &s;olution of ar&s;e|nic given internally, after her feveri&s;h &s;ymptoms were abat<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">, by the u&s;e of &s;aline medicines, alleviating her pains by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">|ates, and keeping the bowels open by mild aperients, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> enabled to leave her bed, was totally freed from all pain, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> has continued apparently &s;o well for &s;ome months, that &s;he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">|joys a &s;tate of health &s;uperior to what &s;he experienced for &s;ome time before her indi&s;po&s;ition began to be &s;o &s;evere. I &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> have ob&s;erved, that &s;he made u&s;e of an injection for<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> decoction of hemlock and poppy heads.</P>
<P>In all ca&s;es of cancer, whether occult or ulcerated, the pati|ents &s;hould be kept on cooling diet, milk whey, and milk, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the u&s;e of warm baths, and, perhaps, whil&s;t the cancer <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the former &s;tate, wearing a hare or rabbit &s;kin over the part affected is extremely u&s;eful&mdash;the pain &s;hould be moderated by occa&s;ional bleeding, cooling purges, a &s;pare, thin, cooling di<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t, and gentle opiates; cordials, exerci&s;e, and whatever <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> too quick motion to the circulating fluids, or increa&s;e the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the machine, &s;hould be avoided.</P>
<P>The purgatives proper to be u&s;ed are Glauber's &s;alt, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> po|lychre&s;t, or &s;ome other of the cooling and gentle purgatives, (171, 172)&mdash;and in ca&s;es of febrile affections, &s;aline <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, or nitrous medicines, (No. 1, 2.) are advi&s;eable&mdash;and for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, milk and water, or &s;ar&s;aparilla decoction.</P>
<P><PB N="479" REF="028021_0475_0FD673D8B25CC2E0">
Hemlock joined with bark, and &s;mall do&s;es of corro&s;ive &s;ub|limate, has by &s;ome been ranked among the mo&s;t efficacious of all cancerous medicines&mdash;half a grain of the latter of which, di&s;&s;olved in &s;pirits of wine, and given in cancers of the face and no&s;e, night and morning, has been recommended as very beneficial&mdash;in cancers of the brea&s;t, an infu&s;ion of deadly night|&s;hade has been con&s;idered as the mo&s;t u&s;eful.</P>
<P>Of hemlock, the fre&s;h juice is thought more efficacious than the extract, beginning with four or five drops, and gradually increa&s;ing the do&s;e.</P>
<P>With re&s;pect to external applications, various are the materi|als recommended in this point, &s;uch as poultices of hemlock, goo&s;e-gra&s;s, carrot, &s;olutions of ar&s;enic, lead, acetated ceru&s;s, fixable air, &amp;c. but as it is our province only to treat on com|plaints medically, we mu&s;t refer our readers to the works of &s;ur|gical authors on this part of the &s;ubject.</P>
