<HEAD>&sect; 3. LEUCORRHOEA;</HEAD>
<P>&s;o called from the Greek <HI>leukos,</HI> albos, white, and <HI>reo,</HI> fluo, to flow, becau&s;e of the di&s;charge being generally of a white co|lour&mdash;al&s;o FLUOR ALBUS, white flux&mdash;it is vulgarly called the WHITES, for the &s;ame rea&s;on&mdash;this is a di&s;charge of &s;erous or mucous matter, &s;ometimes white, or others yellowi&s;h, brown|i&s;h, or rather greeni&s;h, from the womb and vagina.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. At fir&s;t this di&s;charge is mild and &s;erous, which afterwards, by not pa&s;&s;ing freely off, or &s;tagnating, becomes more thick and acrimonious, and will be different with regard to its colour and &s;mell&mdash;indeed, tho&s;e &s;ymptoms which we have enumerated as concomitants to a morbid flux of the men&s;es from a pa&s;&s;ive cau&s;e, generally here attend&mdash;and when the di&s;charge is exce&s;&s;ive, or of any long continuance, pains and weakne&s;s of the loins&mdash;indige&s;tion&mdash;and other &s;ymptoms of debility&mdash;&s;wel|ling of the eye-lids&mdash;thick urine&mdash;palpitation of the heart&mdash;frequent faintings, are almo&s;t always con&s;tant concomitants;&mdash;but in the early &s;tages they do not frequently make their ap|pearance to any great degree.</P>
<P>Indeed, the colour and con&s;i&s;tence of the di&s;charge alter, from a variety of circum&s;tances, according to the nature and dura|tion of the di&s;ea&s;e, &s;ea&s;on, climate, and con&s;titution&mdash;in warm weather, gro&s;s habits neglecting to keep the parts clean, from quantity or acrimony painful excoriations are occa&s;ioned, in&s;o|much, that &s;ometimes it has been difficult to di&s;tingui&s;h it from the effect of &s;ome venereal taint&mdash;and here it will be nece&s;&s;ary to advert to &s;ome concomitant circum&s;tances&mdash;if a di&s;charge comes on &s;uddenly, with &s;ymptoms of heat and pain&mdash;if it is not attended with weakne&s;s or pain in the back&mdash;if the patient appears to be of a healthful &s;trong &s;tamina&mdash;has had no chil|dren&mdash;no mi&s;carriages&mdash;nor &s;evere or copious flow of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|&s;es&mdash;if the di&s;charge &s;hould be thin and much di&s;coloured at fir&s;t, we may then &s;u&s;pect &s;omething of venereal affection in the ca&s;e&mdash;indeed, I have known many cured of what they called the whites by means to which a virulent gleet, or clap, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> readily yield.</P>
<P>However, the WHITES often occur in women who are &s;ubject to too copious a flow of the men&s;es, or have them too frequent|ly return, and are liable to this from cau&s;es which weaken the ve&s;&s;els of the womb and vagina&mdash;or are of a relaxed or debili|tated con&s;titution&mdash;hence it generally affects women advanced in life, particularly tho&s;e who have had children, have often mi&s;carried, men&s;truated irregularly&mdash;al&s;o tho&s;e who lead an in|active life; tho&s;e who are full and jolly, and whole &s;olids are
<PB N="501" REF="028021_0497_0FD673F2390DCA08">
loo&s;e and flabby&mdash;the more recent and whiter the di&s;charge, the more ea&s;y to cure the di&s;ea&s;e; the longer the continuance, and the more green or brown the colour, the more difficult.</P>
<P>CAUSES. Are all &s;uch as occa&s;ion a collection of &s;erum, and weaken the ve&s;&s;els of the parts affected, or the habit in ge|neral&mdash;hence living in moi&s;t air&mdash;feeding on vi&s;cid too food, lead|ing a life of indolence&mdash;u&s;ing too frequently warm baths; an immoderate flow, or an ob&s;truction of the men&s;es; or it may be occa&s;ioned by a tran&s;lation of humours to the womb and vagina.</P>
<P>CURE. Now it will appear obvious, as we con&s;ider the nature of the di&s;ea&s;e, whether <HI>local</HI> or <HI>general,</HI> &s;o mu&s;t we adapt our remedies, whether it depends upon the relaxed &s;tate of the ve&s;&s;els of the womb primarily and principally, or we attribute it to the debilitated &s;tate of the &s;y&s;tem; in the former, we may place much dependance upon external applications of the a&s;trin|gent cla&s;s; in the latter, &s;ome medicines internally &s;hould be exhibited, which will not only give &s;trength to the con&s;titution, but contribute to maintain it in that &s;tate&mdash;hence, then, accor|ding to the different circum&s;tances of the con&s;titution, we mu&s;t regulate our modes of cure.</P>
<P>When it occurs in tho&s;e who live &s;edentary and indolent lives, indulging in luxuries, and &s;upporting them&s;elves by a full rich diet, by which the habit will be loaded with gro&s;s humours, their mode &s;hould be altered to a diet which is more &s;paring, and a cooling regimen, having frequent recour&s;e to purgatives, and a more active &s;tate of life; but to tho&s;e of a more weak, relaxed &s;tate of &s;olids, we mu&s;t invigorate the con&s;titution in the &s;ame manner as directed in too copious flow of the men&s;es from a pa&s;&s;ive cau&s;e, (500.)&mdash;here it is of great u&s;e to keep the parts clean by frequent partial baths of cold water; and after gentle evacuations, in tho&s;e who have lived indolently and luxuriou&s;ly, an a&s;tringent wa&s;h of the gentle kind may be made u&s;e of, &s;uch as the re&s;tringent injection, (No. 165.) with the addition of eleven ounces of infu&s;ion of ro&s;es; in tho&s;e of relax|ed habits, injections of bark with alum, alum water, infu&s;ion of tormentil roots, with litharge water, or &s;ome &s;uch a&s;trin|gent preparations; for they are &s;aid to dimini&s;h the di&s;charge, and, in recent ca&s;es, entirely remove it.</P>
<P>Sometimes from a long continuance of this di&s;ea&s;e, the hu|mours are apt to be acrimonious and irritating, and a&s;&s;i&s;t in &s;upporting the di&s;charge; then hart&s;horn jellies, or tho&s;e of i&s;in|gla&s;s, are agreeable and u&s;eful auxiliaries.</P>
<P>Sometimes tho&s;e &s;timulants which act upon the urinary pa&s;|&s;ages, and communicate their effects to the womb and vagina.
<PB N="502" REF="028021_0498_0FD67461EFDF37F0">
have been thought beneficial in the&s;e ca&s;es; Spani&s;h flies in tincture, joined with &s;ome of the preparation of iron, and bark, have produced good effects; bal&s;am of copaiva; bal&s;am of tur|pentine, and tho&s;e of this cla&s;s, have been con&s;idered as u&s;eful.</P>
<P>But, in ca&s;es of long &s;tanding, I have &s;een much benefit de|rived, during the u&s;e of a&s;tringent medicines, from a &s;timulat|ing plai&s;ter or bli&s;ter applied to the region of the &s;acrum, or lower vertebrae of the back.</P>
<P>If the complaint proceeds from, or is &s;upported by a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;tate of fluids, <HI>that</HI> &s;hould be corrected by the u&s;e of anti<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">|als and mercurials, taken for &s;ome time, with a decoction of the woods in lime water; and in this &s;tate of the con&s;titution i&s;&s;ues are extremely &s;erviceable; after this cour&s;e, local applica|tions, and a&s;tringents internally bid fair to produce th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;e good effects, which they fail of doing without &s;uch an alterative <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>&sect; 4. We are now to treat of the men&s;es in a different <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of view, where they are either <HI>retained, &s;uppre&s;&s;ed, or flow with difficulty,</HI> and the&s;e are all compri&s;ed under the term AM<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">|RHOEA, from the Greek <HI>a, alpha,</HI> non, <HI>mene,</HI> men&s;is, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and <HI>r<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">,</HI> fluo, to flow.</P>
<P>THE FIRST OF THESE, or THE RETENTION of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> happens in women arrived at a &s;tate of puberty, in whom <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">|ter the u&s;ual time of their fir&s;t appearance, they do not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> manife&s;t them&s;elves; and when at the &s;ame time there <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> various affections, &s;hewing the machine to be in a &s;tate of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|ea&s;e.</P>
<P>THE SECOND, or a SUPPRESSION, in adults, in whom <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> men&s;es, which have been accu&s;tomed to flow, are &s;topt.</P>
<P>THE THIRD is where they do flow, but too &s;paringly, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> with pain.</P>
<P>Now in the fir&s;t of the&s;e, that di&s;ea&s;e, CHLOROSIS, from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Greek <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI> viridis, green, or <HI>pallidus,</HI> pale, from the co|lour of the countenance, called here the GREEN SICKNESS, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> induced.</P>
<P>DESCRIPTION. This complaint is attended with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> pallid or yellowi&s;h countence, una&s;&s;ociated with any yellow<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> of the eyes, like that in the jaundice&mdash;&s;mall and weak pul&s;e, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the &s;ame time languid, a want of alertne&s;s in motion, with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and debility&mdash;the patients are affected with nau&s;ea, vo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|ing, often throw up wind, and have pain in the &s;tomach&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> though they want appetite for common food, have a de&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;uch things as are not u&s;ed for food, as chalk, &s;lates, or other ab&s;orbents, green fruit&mdash;they are co&s;tive, and have other &s;ymp|toms of indige&s;tion; the whole body is pale and flaccid; and the feet and great part of the body become pa&s;ty&mdash;by quick
<PB N="503" REF="028021_0499_0FD6745236A31750">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> particularly going up &s;tairs, or climbing up hill, the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is laborious&mdash;palpitation affects the heart&mdash;fainting&mdash;&s;ometimes a pain or giddine&s;s in the head comes on, but <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> certainly pains of the back, loins, and hips. Now the&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> are among the certain &s;igns of this di&s;ea&s;e, when <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">o any con&s;iderable degree; indeed, in the earlier &s;tag|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> mo&s;t of them prevail, but not to that exce&s;s.</P>
<P>As the men&s;es appear at different ages, we mu&s;t not &s;tile a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> di&s;ea&s;ed becau&s;e they flow not at a given time&mdash;but, if, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the common time has elap&s;ed, there appear evident &s;igns <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> indi&s;po&s;ition, &s;uch as we have recited in their inferior degree, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> numerous, we need not he&s;itate in pronouncing the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a di&s;ea&s;e.</P>
<P>CAUSES. A debility of the &s;y&s;tem in general, bringing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;imilar &s;tate in the ve&s;&s;els of the womb, whence a general <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and local uterine circulation, occa&s;ioning the men&s;es to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">tained.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">. The indications are, to &s;trengthen the &s;y&s;tem; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> the action of the ve&s;&s;els, particularly tho&s;e of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;and the&s;e are done chiefly by bark tormentil root, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, joined with preparations of iron and bitters&mdash;the pa|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="5 letters"> ought to live on a generous diet, go into the cold bath <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> exerci&s;e&mdash;the&s;e will invigorate the con&s;titution&mdash;after|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">s, aloetic purges are u&s;eful&mdash;frictions of the lower extre|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">, and bathing the feet in warm water&mdash;indeed, all tho&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="6 letters">ives are of &s;ervice which &s;timulate the rectum, as aloes, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, black hellebore, and calomel; for they communicate <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> effects to the ve&s;&s;els of the womb.</P>
<P>Bli&s;tering the lower part of the back, or &s;timulating plai&s;ters <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> there, may be advantageou&s;ly recommended.</P>
<P>There this debility is brought on, as it &s;ometimes is, by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> unea&s;ine&s;s of mind, occa&s;ioned by di&s;appointments, or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> delay in love, matrimony is an efficacious remedy&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> al&s;o have great faith in the electric &s;hock; and, indeed, as &s;timulant, electricity bids fair to be of great &s;ervice.</P>
<P>THE SECOND SPECIES, or SUPPRESSION of the men&s;es ri&s;es <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> different cau&s;e, from &s;ome re&s;i&s;tance in the extremities <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> uterine ve&s;&s;els, originating mo&s;t frequently from &s;pa&s;mo|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> con&s;triction of th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;e ve&s;&s;els, or, according to &s;ome, from a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of them; the former &s;eems to be the general cau&s;e, as it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> its origin from cold, fea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">, irregular pa&s;&s;ions, fullne&s;s, or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;imilar, and this complaint comes on after the men|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters"> di&s;charges have gone on for &s;ome time regularly; for, on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> fir&s;t appearance, they will &s;ometimes &s;top, and not return <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> year, or perhaps a longer &s;pace&mdash;but, under this circum|&s;tance,
<PB N="504" REF="028021_0500_0FD67468C3943AB0">
