<P>CHARACTERISTIC SIGNS. A large head, &s;welling <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> on the &s;ore part&mdash;tumefied knees and wri&s;ts, depre&s;&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, di&s;tended belly, the re&s;t of the body wa&s;ting away.</P>
<P>CURE. The indications are, to increa&s;e the tone of the &s;to|mach, improve the dige&s;tive powers, and invigorate the &s;y&s;|tem.</P>
<P>In the fir&s;t place, however, &s;ome of the &s;ymptoms are to be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">eviated, as the &s;tomach and bowels are apt to be foul, at the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> time the latter di&s;tended with wind; they &s;hould be emp|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> by gentle vomits and mild purgatives&mdash;&s;mall do&s;es of ipe|cacuanha, or of tartarized antimony, &s;hould be given for the fir&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; and for the other, rhubarb and calomel, or Polychre&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; rhubarb is the mo&s;t eligible, as it is both bitter and a&s;trin|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">, therefore a good &s;timulant and tonic&mdash;the vomit may now <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> then be repeated, as it will, by the &s;hocks it gives to the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">els and the other vi&s;cera, of the belly, a&s;&s;i&s;t in taking off, or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">eventing the ob&s;truction and enlargement that often occur in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>The belly al&s;o may be rubbed with &s;timulant liniments, as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> liniment, or No. 182. which has been &s;trongly recom|mended&mdash;indeed, any of the joints which are &s;welled may be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> with this twice a day&mdash;and, perhaps, it will be more effica|cious if it is applied after friction of the parts with a flannel <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the fire&mdash;<HI>&s;ca<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e oil</HI> has al&s;o for this purpo&s;e been much <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, which is u&s;ed by the inhabitants of the we&s;tern parts of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in the following manner;&mdash;fir&s;t, the wri&s;ts and ankles <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> rubbed well with oil in the evening, this immediately rai&s;es febrile affections for &s;everal hours; when the fever &s;ub&s;ides, the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">me parts are rubbed again the night following, and repeated as long as the rubbing excites &s;imilar effects&mdash;when, by rubbing the&s;e parts alone, not any febrile affections can be excited, the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">me proce&s;s is performed, and continued in the &s;ame manner on the knees and elbows&mdash;then afterwards down the back bones, and on the &s;ides&mdash;and when no fever is rai&s;ed by this operation, a flannel &s;hirt dipped into the oil is put upon the patient's body,
