<P>The chief tonics employed in the&s;e ca&s;es are bark and &s;teel&mdash;of the former, from the nau&s;eou&s;ne&s;s of the ta&s;te, it is &s;carce po&s;|&s;ible to get down a &s;ufficient quantity to render it effectual&mdash;however, it may be applied externally to the wri&s;ts, by form|ing the extract into plai&s;ter, or quilting the powder in &s;oft lin|en, (260.) applied in the&s;e modes I have been informed that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> has proved effectual; but I &s;hould prefer its being brought into contact with the coats of the &s;tomach immediately, as on that, it appears to me, depends its greate&s;t efficacy.</P>
<P>Steel, as a preventive, has had its warm advocates, who, in order to be able to di&s;tingui&s;h whether a child will become ric|ketty, point out the following &s;ymptoms:&mdash;a palene&s;s and &s;well|ing of the countenance, and in that part of the cheeks, which &s;hould be naturally red, a yellow colour approaching to that of &s;ulphur; in which ca&s;e, five grains of the filings of iron, and as much rhubarb, with ten grains of &s;ugar, &s;hould be given every morning fa&s;ting and evening&mdash;but &s;hould this prove too purga|tive at fir&s;t, one do&s;e &s;hould only be given every day&mdash;after <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> month's continuance, a keen appetite en&s;ues, quick dige&s;tion and a copious flow of urine&mdash;the fullne&s;s of the face, and yellow|ne&s;s of the complexion, by degrees are removed, and natural countenance and firmne&s;s of the body gradually re&s;tored&mdash;and this practice, it is &s;aid, has never failed of &s;ucce&s;s in any one in|&s;tance.</P>
<P>Five grains of ammoniacal iron may be given twice a day <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a month, or longer, interpo&s;ing occa&s;ionally aperient do&s;es of rhubarb; but, in ca&s;es of feveri&s;h di&s;po&s;ition, bark, with the vi|triolic acid, is more eligible.</P>
<P>In ca&s;es of rickets, prepared kali, (177.) half a dram di&s;&s;olv|ed in eight ounces of bark decoction, four ounces taken every day cured a boy of &s;even years old, who has &s;o much <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that his inferior extremities had become &s;tiff and immoveable&mdash;the body flaccid, he was much worn away by a loo&s;ene&s;s and con&s;tant &s;weatings, and had five fi&s;tulous ulcers all di&s;charging at the &s;ame time&mdash;in the cour&s;e of one month from beginning to take the medicines he ro&s;e from his bed, and walked with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;upport&mdash;the bark was then changed to madder, and in le&s;s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> four months he walked with a crutch, and by that time the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> were nearly healed&mdash;the watery &s;olutions of kali have in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ricketty people been &s;ucce&s;sful.</P>
<P>Strong beer, porter, and wine have been recommended; but I &s;hould rather think them pernicious, the two former from
