their vi&s;cidity, and the latter from its pronene&s;s to become <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>But the remedy mo&s;t to be depended upon is <HI>cold bathing,</HI> or <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in the &s;ea,</HI> and is certainly the mo&s;t powerful preventive. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">otland it has long been the practice with people of all ranks <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> wa&s;h their children from the time of their birth with cold <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; and, from the time that they are a month old, the &s;upe|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> cla&s;s dip them entirely in cold water every morning&mdash;and, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> this practice has been pur&s;ued, Dr. CULLEN a&s;&s;erts, that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> never met with any in&s;tance of rickets&mdash;among the common people, though they wa&s;h their children with cold water, they do <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;o commonly practi&s;e immer&s;ion; and when among&s;t the&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> with ca&s;es of rickets, he pre&s;cribes cold bathing, which is accordingly checked the progre&s;s of the di&s;ea&s;e, and &s;eems &s;ometimes entirely to have cured it.</P>
<P>With re&s;pect to diet, &s;trong objections have by &s;ome been &s;tart|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> milk, and where nur&s;es are apt to give large quantities of a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> kind, it may certainly be detrimental, becau&s;e it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> weaken and relax the &s;tomach, fill it and the bowels with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> humours, and al&s;o the machine with too great a load of wa|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">, ill-dige&s;ted fluids, and hence favour the coming on of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; but where the milk is of proper con&s;i&s;tence, and does <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> appear to di&s;agree, it may be per&s;i&s;ted in&mdash;chicken or thin <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> broth, beef-tea with rice, or rice with cow's milk, proper|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, may be occa&s;ionally given&mdash;and leavened bread is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to the unfermented farinaceous &s;ub&s;tances, of which <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> panada may be made, and now and then mixed with &s;mall <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of aromatic &s;pecies.</P>
<P>Te&s;taceous powders, crabs eyes, &amp;c. (191.) may be given by them&s;elves, or mixed with the food, as they are ta&s;tele&s;s; for of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> we have accounts of their utility.</P>
<P>Exerci&s;e in the&s;e ca&s;es is e&s;&s;entially nece&s;&s;ary; but it &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the gentler &s;ort, and in an horizontal po&s;ition, le&s;t, by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> upright, &s;ome di&s;tortion &s;hould take place&mdash;here cradles may be of u&s;e, or mattre&s;&s;es laid upon &s;wings, and judiciou&s;ly <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to &s;ecure the little infant from falling out, which &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> fixed in the open air, in &s;ome &s;hady place, protected from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> too powerful force of the &s;un&mdash;nur&s;es &s;hould avoid carrying <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in this di&s;ea&s;e always in one arm, (126.) nor &s;hould they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, or to&s;s them up much, for the brea&s;t may by the&s;e means be greatly injured, by the pre&s;&s;ure of the thumb and finger on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ide the brea&s;t bone, from indentation or bending of the ribs inwards.</P>
<P>And with re&s;pect to &s;ituation, as it has been ob&s;erved, that people who live in damp moi&s;t places, where the air in common
<PB N="524" REF="028021_0520_0FD674827906D8B0">
abounds too much with watery particles, are more &s;ubject to this di&s;ea&s;e than tho&s;e who live in dry airy &s;ituations, particu|larly in Holland, all &s;uch &s;hould be particularly avoided&mdash;and by ob&s;erving the rules here laid down, we may be almo&s;t always &s;ucce&s;sful in preventing, and very often in curing this malady, if at the &s;ame time care is taken to pre&s;erve cleanline&s;s, which is not the lea&s;t u&s;eful rule in our conduct.</P>
